text: Recurrent Neural Network Grammars
heading: title

text: In this paper , we introduce recurrent neural network grammars ( RNNGs ; 2 ) , a new generative probabilistic model of sentences that explicitly models nested , hierarchical relationships among words and phrases .
heading: Introduction

text: RNNGs operate via a recursive syntactic process reminiscent of probabilistic context - free grammar generation , but decisions are parameterized using RNNs that condition on the entire syntactic derivation history , greatly relaxing context - free independence assumptions .
heading: Introduction

text: We give two variants of the algorithm , one for parsing ( given an observed sentence , transform it into a tree ) , and one for generation .
heading: Introduction

text: The discriminative model also lets us use ancestor sampling to obtain samples of parse trees for sentences , and this is used to solve a second practical challenge with RNNGs : approximating the marginal likelihood and MAP tree of a sentence under the generative model .
heading: Refer to for an example .

text: We present a simple importance sampling algorithm which uses samples from the discriminative parser to solve inference problems in the generative model ( 5 ) .
heading: Refer to for an example .

text: For the discriminative model , we used hidden dimensions of 128 and 2 - layer LSTMs ( larger numbers of dimensions reduced validation set performance ) .
heading: Model and training parameters .

text: For the generative model , we used 256 dimensions and 2 layer LSTMs .
heading: Model and training parameters .

text: For both models , we tuned the dropout rate to maximize validation set likelihood , obtaining optimal rates of 0.2 ( discriminative ) and 0.3 ( generative ) .
heading: Model and training parameters .

text: For the sequential LSTM baseline for the language model , we also found an optimal dropout rate of 0.3 .
heading: Model and training parameters .

text: For training we used stochastic gradient descent with a learning rate of 0.1 .
heading: Model and training parameters .

text: Cloze - driven Pretraining of Self - attention Networks
We present a new approach for pretraining a bi-directional transformer model that provides significant performance gains across a variety of language understanding problems .
heading: abstract

text: Language model pretraining has recently been shown to provide significant performance gains for a range of challenging language understanding problems .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper , we show that even larger performance gains are possible by jointly pretraining both directions of a large language - model - inspired self - attention cloze model .

text: Our bi-directional transformer architecture predicts every token in the training data ( ) .

text: We achieve this by introducing a cloze - style training objective where the model must predict the center word given left - to - right and right - to - left context representations .

text: Parsing as Language Modeling

We recast syntactic parsing as a language modeling problem and use recent advances in neural network language modeling to achieve a new state of the art for constituency Penn Treebank parsing - 93.8 F 1 on section 23 , using 2 - 21 as training , 24 as development , plus tri-training .

text: Improving Coreference Resolution by Learning Entity - Level Distributed Representations
heading: title

text: In this work , we instead train a deep neural network to build distributed representations of pairs of coreference clusters .
heading: Introduction

text: This captures entity - level information with a large number of learned , continuous features instead of a small number of hand - crafted categorical ones .
heading: Introduction

text: Using the cluster - pair representations , our network learns when combining two coreference clusters is desirable .
heading: Introduction

text: At test time it builds up coreference clusters incrementally , starting with each mention in its own cluster and then merging a pair of clusters each step .
heading: Introduction

text: It makes these decisions with a novel easy - first cluster - ranking procedure that combines the strengths of cluster - ranking ( Rahman and and easy - first coreference algorithms .
heading: Introduction

text: We address this by using a learning - to - search algorithm inspired by SEARN to train our neural network .
heading: Introduction

text: This approach allows the model to learn which action ( a cluster merge ) available from the current state ( a partially completed coreference clustering ) will eventually lead to a high - scoring coreference partition .
heading: Introduction

text: Our mention - ranking model surpasses all previous systems .
heading: Final System Performance

text: The cluster - ranking model improves results further across both languages and all evaluation metrics , demonstrating the utility of incorporating entity - level information .
heading: Final System Performance

text: End - to - end Deep Reinforcement Learning Based Coreference Resolution
heading: title

text: In this paper , we propose a goal - directed endto - end deep reinforcement learning framework to resolve coreference as shown in .
heading: Introduction

text: Specifically , we leverage the neural architecture in as our policy network , which includes learning span representation , scoring potential entity mentions , and generating a probability distribution over all possible coreference linking actions from the current mention to its antecedents .
heading: Introduction

text: Once a sequence of linking actions are made , our reward function is used to measure how good the generated coreference clusters are , which is directly related to coreference evaluation metrics .
heading: Introduction

text: Besides , we introduce an entropy regularization term to encourage exploration and prevent the policy from prematurely converging to a bad local optimum .
heading: Introduction

text: Finally , we update the regularized policy network parameters based on the rewards associated with sequences of sampled actions , which are computed on the whole input document .
heading: Introduction

text: Higher - order Coreference Resolution with Coarse - to - fine Inference
heading: title

text: We introduce an approximation of higher - order inference that uses the span - ranking architecture from in an iterative manner .
heading: Introduction

text: At each iteration , the antecedent distribution is used as an attention mechanism to optionally update existing span representations , enabling later corefer - Speaker 1 : U m and think that is what 's - Go ahead Linda .
heading: Introduction

text: To alleviate computational challenges from this higher - order inference , we also propose a coarseto - fine approach that is learned with a single endto - end objective .
heading: Introduction

text: We introduce a less accurate but more efficient coarse factor in the pairwise scoring function .
heading: Introduction

text: This additional factor enables an extra pruning step during inference that reduces the number of antecedents considered by the more accurate but inefficient fine factor .
heading: Introduction

text: Intuitively , the model cheaply computes a rough sketch of likely antecedents before applying a more expensive scoring function .
heading: Introduction

text: Results
The baseline relative to our contributions is the span - ranking model from augmented with both ELMo and hyperparameter tuning , which achieves 72.3 F1 .
heading: Results

text: Our full approach achieves 73.0 F1 , setting a new state of the art for coreference resolution .
heading: Results

text: Despite using far less computation , it outperforms the baseline because the coarse scores s c ( i , j ) can be computed for all antecedents , enabling the model to potentially predict a coreference link between any two spans in the document .
heading: Results

text: As a result , we observe a much higher recall when adopting the coarse - to - fine approach .
heading: Results

text: We also observe further improvement by including the second - order inference ( Section 3 ) .
heading: Results

text: A Mention - Ranking Model for Abstract Anaphora Resolution
heading: title

text: Current research in anaphora ( or coreference ) resolution is focused on resolving noun phrases referring to concrete objects or entities in the real Leo Born , Juri Opitz and Anette Frank contributed equally to this work .
heading: Introduction

text: Our model is inspired by the mention - ranking model for coreference resolution and combines it with a Siamese Net , for learning similarity between sentences .
heading: Introduction

text: Given an anaphoric sentence ( AntecS in ( 1 ) ) and a candidate antecedent ( any constituent in a given context , e.g. being obsoleted by microprocessor - based machines in ( 1 ) ) , the LSTM - Siamese Net learns representations for the candidate and the anaphoric sentence in a shared space .
heading: Introduction

text: These representations are combined into a joint representation used to calculate a score that characterizes the relation between them .
heading: Introduction

text: The learned score is used to select the highest - scoring antecedent candidate for the given anaphoric sentence and hence its anaphor .
heading: Introduction

text: We consider one anaphor at a time and provide the embedding of the context of the anaphor and the embedding of the head of the anaphoric phrase to the input to characterize each individual anaphorsimilar to the encoding proposed by for individuating multiply occurring predicates in SRL .
heading: Introduction

text: With deeper inspection we show that the model learns a relation between the anaphor in the anaphoric sentence and its antecedent .
heading: Introduction

text: It produces large amounts of instances and is easily adaptable to other languages .
heading: Introduction

text: Our Tensor Flow 2 implementation of the model and scripts for data extraction are available at : https://github.com/amarasovic / neural-abstract-anaphora .

text: Learning Global Features for Coreference Resolution
There is compelling evidence that coreference prediction would benefit from modeling global information about entity - clusters .
heading: abstract

text: In this work , we posit that global context is indeed necessary for further improvements in coreference resolution , but argue that informative cluster , rather than mention , level features are very difficult to devise , limiting their effectiveness .
heading: Introduction

text: Accordingly , we instead propose to learn representations of mention clusters by embedding them sequentially using a recurrent neural network ( shown in Section 4 ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Our model has no manually defined cluster features , but instead learns a global representation from the individual mentions present in each cluster .
heading: Introduction

text: We incorporate these representations into a mention - ranking style coreference system .
heading: Introduction

text: The entire model , including the recurrent neural network and the mention - ranking sub-system , is trained end - to - end on the coreference task .
heading: Introduction

text: We train the model as a local classifier with fixed context ( that is , as a history - based model ) .
heading: Introduction

text: For training , we use document - size minibatches , which allows for efficient pre-computation of RNN states , and we minimize the loss described in Section 5 with AdaGrad ( after clipping LSTM gradients to lie ( elementwise ) in ( ?10 , 10 ) ) .
heading: Features

text: We find that the initial learning rate chosen for AdaGrad has a significant impact on results , and we choose learning rates for each layer out of { 0.1 , 0.02 , 0.01 , 0.002 , 0.001 } .
heading: Features

text: In experiments , we set ha ( x n ) , h c ( x n ) , and h ( m ) to be ? R 200 , and hp ( x n , y) ? R 700 .
heading: Features

text: We use a single - layer LSTM ( without " peep - hole " connections ) , as implemented in the element - rnn library .
heading: Features

text: For regularization , we apply Dropout with a rate of 0.4 before applying the linear weights u , and we also apply Dropout with a rate of 0.3 to the LSTM states before forming the dot -product scores .
heading: Features

text: Code for our system is available at https : //github.com/swiseman/nn_coref .
heading: Features

text: The system makes use of a GPU for training , and trains in about two hours .
heading: Features

We see a statistically significant improvement of over 0.8 Co NLL points over the previous state of the art , and the highest F 1 scores to date on all three CoNLL metrics .
heading: Results

text: In we see that the RNN improves performance over all , with the most dramatic improve - ments on non-anaphoric pronouns , though errors are also decreased significantly for non-anaphoric nominal and proper mentions that follow at least one mention with the same head .
heading: Results

text: Importantly , the RNN performance is significantly better than that of the Avg baseline , which barely improves over mention - ranking , even with oracle history .

text: Learning Word Representations with Cross - Sentence Dependency for End - to - End Co -reference Resolution
heading: title

text: In this work , we present a word embedding model that learns cross - sentence dependency for improving end - to - end co-reference resolution ( E2E - CR ) .
heading: abstract

text: While the traditional E2E - CR model generates word representations by running long short - term memory ( LSTM ) recurrent neural networks on each sentence of an input article or conversation separately , we propose linear sentence linking and attentional sentence linking models to learn crosssentence dependency .
heading: abstract

text: Co-reference resolution requires models to cluster mentions that refer to the same physical entities .
heading: Introduction

text: To solve the problem that traditional LSTM encoders , which treat the input sentences as a batch , lack an ability to capture cross - sentence dependency , and to avoid the time complexity and difficulties of training the model concatenating all input sentences , we propose a cross - sentence encoder for end - to - end co-reference ( E2E - CR ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Borrowing the idea of an external memory module from , an external memory block containing syntactic and semantic information from context sentences is added to the standard LSTM model .
heading: Introduction

text: With this context memory block , the proposed model is able to encode input sentences as a batch , and also calculate the representations of input words by taking both target sentences and context sentences into consideration .
heading: Introduction

text: In practice , the LSTM modules applied in our model have 200 output units .
heading: Model and Hyperparameter Setup

text: In ASL , we calculate cross - sentence dependency using a multilayer perceptron with one hidden layer consisting of 150 hidden units .
heading: Model and Hyperparameter Setup

text: The initial learning rate is set as 0.001 and decays 0.001 % every 100 steps .
heading: Model and Hyperparameter Setup

text: The model is optimized with the Adam algorithm ( Kingma and Ba , 2014 ) .
heading: Model and Hyperparameter Setup

text: We randomly select up to 40 continuous sentences for training if the input is too long .
heading: Model and Hyperparameter Setup

text: Experiment Results and Discussion
Comparing with the baseline model that achieved 67.2 % F1 score , the ASL model improved the performance by 0.6 % and achieved 67.8 % average F1 .
heading: Experiment Results and Discussion

text: show that the models that consider cross - sentence dependency significantly outperform the baseline model , which encodes each sentence from the input document separately .
heading: Experiment Results and Discussion

text: Experiments also indicated that the ASL model has better performance than the LSL model , since it summarizes extracts context information with an attention mechanism instead of simply viewing sentence - level embeddings .
heading: Experiment Results and Discussion

text: Coreference Resolution with Entity Equalization
Here we propose an approach that provides an entity - level representation in a simple and intuitive manner , and also facilitates end - to - end optimization .
heading: Introduction

text: Our " Entity Equalization " approach posits that each entity should be represented via the sum of its corresponding mention representations .
heading: Introduction

text: Similar to recent coreference models , our approach uses contextual embeddings as input mention representations .
heading: Introduction

text: While previous approaches employed the ELMo model , we propose to use BERT embeddings , motivated by the impressive empirical performance of BERT on other tasks .
heading: Introduction

text: We show that this can be done by using BERT in a fully convolutional manner .
heading: Introduction

text: Results
Our baseline is the span - ranking model from with ELMo input features and second - order span representations , which achieves 73.0 % Avg .
heading: Results

text: F1 . Replacing the ELMo features with BERT features achieves 76. 25 % average F1 .
heading: Results

text: Removing the second - order span - representations while using BERT features achieves 76.37 % F1 , achieving higher recall and lower precision on all evaluation metrics , while somewhat surprisingly being better over all .
heading: Results

text: Replacing secondorder span representations with Entity Equalization achieves 76. 64 % average F1 , while also consistently achieving the highest F 1 score on all three evaluation metrics .
heading: Results

text: Our results set a new state of the art for coreference resolution , improving the previous state of the art by 3.6 % average F1 .
heading: Results

text: End - to - end Neural Coreference Resolution
heading: title

text: We introduce the first end - to - end coreference resolution model and show that it significantly outperforms all previous work without using a syntactic parser or handengineered mention detector .
heading: abstract

text: We present the first state - of - the - art neural coreference resolution model that is learned end - toend given only gold mention clusters .
heading: Introduction

text: We demonstrate for the first time that these resources are not required , and in fact performance can be improved significantly without them , by training an end - to - end neural model that jointly learns which spans are entity mentions and how to best cluster them .
heading: Introduction

text: Our model reasons over the space of all spans up to a maximum length and directly optimizes the marginal likelihood of antecedent spans from gold coreference clusters .
heading: Introduction

text: It includes a span - ranking model that decides , for each span , which of the previous spans ( if any ) is a good antecedent .
heading: Introduction

text: At the core of our model are vector embeddings representing spans of text in the document , which combine context - dependent boundary representations with a head - finding attention mechanism over the span .
heading: Introduction

text: The attention component is inspired by parser - derived head - word matching features from previous systems , but is less susceptible to cascading errors .
heading: Introduction

text: Hyperparameters
The word embeddings area fixed concatenation of 300 - dimensional GloVe embeddings and 50 - dimensional embeddings from , both normalized to be unit vectors .
heading: Word representations

heading: Word representations

heading: Word representations

heading: Word representations

text: The hidden states in the LSTMs have 200 dimensions .
heading: Hidden dimensions

text: Each feedforward neural network consists of two hidden layers with 150 dimensions and rectified linear units .
heading: Hidden dimensions

text: We use ADAM for learning with a minibatch size of 1 .
heading: Learning

text: The LSTM weights are initialized with random orthonormal matrices as described in .
heading: Learning

text: We apply 0.5 dropout to the word embeddings and character CNN outputs .
heading: Learning

text: We apply 0.2 dropout to all hidden layers and feature embeddings .
heading: Learning

text: Dropout masks are shared across timesteps to preserve long - distance information as described in .
heading: Learning

text: The learning rate is decayed by 0.1 % every 100 steps .
heading: Learning

text: The model is trained for up to 150 epochs , with early stopping based on the development set .
heading: Learning

text: A Hierarchical Model for Data - to - Text Generation
heading: title

text: Transcribing structured data into natural language descriptions has emerged as a challenging task , referred to as " data - to - text " .
heading: abstract

text: To address these shortcomings , we propose a new structured - data encoder assuming that structures should be hierarchically captured .
heading: Introduction

text: Our contribution focuses on the encoding of the data - structure , thus the decoder is chosen to be a classical module as used in .
heading: Introduction

text: - We model the general structure of the data using a two - level architecture , first encoding all entities on the basis of their elements , then encoding the data structure on the basis of its entities ; - We introduce the Transformer encoder in data - to - text models to ensure robust encoding of each element / entities in comparison to all others , no matter their initial positioning ; - We integrate a hierarchical attention mechanism to compute the hierarchical context fed into the decoder .
heading: Introduction

text: Baselines
Wiseman is a standard encoder - decoder system with copy mechanism .
heading: Baselines

text: Li is a standard encoder - decoder with a delayed copy mechanism : text is first generated with placeholders , which are replaced by salient records extracted from the table by a pointer network .
heading: Baselines

text: Puduppully - plan acts in two steps : a first standard encoder - decoder generates a plan , i.e. a list of salient records from the table ; a second standard encoder - decoder generates text from this plan .
heading: Baselines

text: Puduppully - updt .
heading: Baselines

text: It consists in a standard encoder - decoder , with an added module aimed at updating record representations during the generation process .
heading: Baselines

text: At each decoding step , a gated recurrent network computes which records should be updated and what should be their new representation .
heading: Baselines

text: The size of the record value embeddings and hidden layers of the Transformer encoders are both set to 300 .
heading: Implementation details

text: We use dropout at rate 0.5 .
heading: Implementation details

text: The models are trained with a batch size of 64 .
heading: Implementation details

text: We follow the training procedure in and train the model for a fixed number of 25 K updates , and average the weights of the last 5 checkpoints ( at every 1 K updates ) to ensure more stability across runs .
heading: Implementation details

text: All models were trained with the Adam optimizer ; the initial learning rate is 0.001 , and is reduced by half every 10 K steps .
heading: Implementation details

text: We used beam search with beam size of 5 during inference .
heading: Implementation details

text: All the models are implemented in Open NMT - py .
heading: Implementation details

text: All code is available at https://github.com/KaijuML/data-to-text-hierarchical
heading: Implementation details

text: Second , the comparison between scenario Hierarchical - kv and Hierarchical -k shows that omitting entirely the influence of the record values in the attention mechanism is more effective : this last variant performs slightly better in all metrics excepted CS - R% , reinforcing our intuition that focusing on the structure modeling is an important part of data encoding as well as confirming the intuition explained in Section 3.3 : once an entity is selected , facts about this entity are relevant based on their key , not value which might add noise .

text: Our hierarchical models achieve significantly better scores on all metrics when compared to the flat architecture Wiseman , reinforcing the crucial role of structure in data semantics and saliency .

heading: title

text: Stack - Pointer Networks for Dependency Parsing
In this paper , we propose a novel neural network architecture for dependency parsing , stackpointer networks ( STACKPTR ) .
heading: Introduction

text: STACKPTR is a transition - based architecture , with the corresponding asymptotic efficiency , but still maintains a global view of the sentence that proves essential for achieving competitive accuracy .
heading: Introduction

text: Our STACKPTR parser has a pointer network as its backbone , and is equipped with an internal stack to maintain the order of head words in tree structures .
heading: Introduction

text: The STACKPTR parser performs parsing in an incremental , topdown , depth - first fashion ; at each step , it generates an arc by assigning a child for the headword at the top of the internal stack .
heading: Introduction

text: For fair comparison of the parsing performance , we re-implemented the graph - based Deep Biaffine ( BIAF ) parser , which achieved state - of - the - art results on a wide range of languages .

text: Structured Training for Neural Network Transition - Based Parsing
We present structured perceptron training for neural network transition - based dependency parsing .
heading: abstract

text: Lately , dependency parsing has emerged as a popular approach to this problem due to the availability of dependency treebanks in many languages and the efficiency of dependency parsers .
heading: Introduction

text: In transition - based parsing , sentences are processed in a linear left to right pass ; at each position , the parser needs to choose from a set of possible actions defined by the transition strategy .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , we combine the representational power of neural networks with the superior search enabled by structured training and inference , making our parser one of the most accurate dependency parsers to date .
heading: Introduction

text: As in prior work , we train the neural network to model the probability of individual parse actions .
heading: Introduction

text: Instead , we use the activations from all layers of the neural network as the representation in a structured perceptron model that is trained with beam search and early updates ( Section 3 ) .
heading: Introduction

text: To this end , we generate large quantities of high - confidence parse trees by parsing unlabeled data with two different parsers and selecting only the sentences for which the two parsers produced the same trees ( Section 3.3 ) .
heading: Introduction

text: This approach is known as " tri-training " and we show that it benefits our neural network parser significantly more than other approaches .
heading: Introduction

text: We used the publicly available word2vec 2 tool to learn CBOW embeddings following the sample configuration provided with the tool .

heading: title

text: We modify the neural graphbased approach first proposed by in a few ways to achieve competitive performance : we build a network that 's larger but uses more regularization ; we replace the traditional MLP - based attention mechanism and affine label classifier with biaffine ones ; and rather than using the top recurrent states of the LSTM in the biaffine transformations , we first put them through MLP operations that reduce their dimensionality .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: We choose to optimize with Adam , which ( among other things ) keeps a moving average of the L 2 norm of the gradient for each parameter throughout training and divides the gradient for each parameter by this moving average , ensuring that the magnitude of the gradients will on average be close to one .

text: This form of training , which accounts for model predictions at training time , improves parsing accuracies .
heading: abstract

text: Natural language parsing can be formulated as a series of decisions that read words in sequence and incrementally combine them to form syntactic structures ; this formalization is known as transitionbased parsing , and is often coupled with a greedy search procedure .
heading: Introduction

text: The literature on transition - based parsing is vast , but all works share in common a classification component that takes into account features of the current parser state 1 and predicts the next action to take conditioned on the state .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , we adapt the training criterion so as to explore parser states drawn not only from the training data , but also from the model as it is being learned .
heading: Introduction

text: To do so , we use the method of to dynamically chose an optimal ( relative to the final attachment accuracy ) action given an imperfect history .
heading: Introduction

text: By interpolating between algorithm states sampled from the model and those sampled from the training data , more robust predictions at test time can be made .
heading: Introduction

text: Globally Normalized Transition - Based Neural Networks
We introduce a globally normalized transition - based neural network model that achieves state - of - the - art part - ofspeech tagging , dependency parsing and sentence compression results .
heading: abstract

text: In this work we demonstrate that simple feed - forward networks without any recurrence can achieve comparable or better accuracies than LSTMs , as long as they are globally normalized .
heading: Introduction

text: Our model , described in detail in Section 2 , uses a transition system and feature embeddings as introduced by * On leave from Columbia University ..
heading: Introduction

text: We do not use any recurrence , but perform beam search for maintaining multiple hypotheses and introduce global normalization with a conditional random field ( CRF ) objective to overcome the label bias problem that locally normalized models suffer from .
heading: Introduction

text: Since we use beam inference , we approximate the partition function by summing over the elements in the beam , and use early updates .
heading: Introduction

text: We compute gradients based on this approximate global normalization and perform full backpropagation training of all neural network parameters based on the CRF loss .
heading: Introduction

text: BRIDGING THE DOMAIN GAP IN CROSS - LINGUAL DOCUMENT CLASSIFICATION
Recent developments in cross - lingual understanding ( XLU ) has made progress in this area , trying to bridge the language barrier using language universal representations .

We combine state - of - the - art cross - lingual methods with recently proposed methods for weakly supervised learning such as unsupervised pre-training and unsupervised data augmentation to simultaneously close both the language gap and the domain gap in XLU .
In particular , we focus on two approaches for domain adaptation .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The first method is based on masked language model ( MLM ) pre-training ( as in ) using unlabeled target language corpora .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The second method is unsupervised data augmentation ( UDA ) ) , where synthetic paraphrases are generated from the unlabeled corpus , and the model is trained on a label consistency loss .

text: Neural Attentive Bag - of - Entities Model for Text Classification
heading: title

text: The source code of the proposed model is available online at https://github.com/wikipedia2vec/wikipedia2vec .
heading: abstract

text: This study proposes the Neural Attentive Bagof - Entities ( NABoE ) model , which is a neural network model that addresses the text classification problem by modeling the semantics in the target documents using entities in the KB .
heading: Introduction

text: For each entity name in a document ( e.g. , " Apple " ) , our model first detects entities that maybe referred to by this name ( e.g. , Apple Inc. , Apple ( food ) ) , and then represents the document using the weighted average of the embeddings of these entities .
heading: Introduction

text: The weights are computed using a novel neural attention mechanism that enables the model to focus on a small subset of the entities that are less ambiguous in meaning and more relevant to the document .
heading: Introduction

text: In other words , the attention mechanism is designed to compute weights by jointly addressing entity linking and entity salience detection tasks .
heading: Introduction

text: The model was trained using mini-batch SGD with its learning rate controlled by Adam and its mini-batch size set to 32 .

text: Graph Convolutional Networks for Text Classification
In this work , we propose a new graph neural networkbased method for text classification .
heading: Introduction

text: We construct a single large graph from an entire corpus , which contains words and documents as nodes .
heading: Introduction

text: We model the graph with a Graph Convolutional Network ( GCN ) , a simple and effective graph neural network that captures high order neighborhoods information .
heading: Introduction

text: The edge between two word nodes is built byword co-occurrence information and the edge between a word node and document node is built using word frequency and word 's document frequency .
heading: Introduction

text: We then turn text classification problem into anode classification problem .

text: Deep Pyramid Convolutional Neural Networks for Text Categorization
heading: title

text: We call it deep pyramid CNN ( DPCNN ) , as the computation time per layer decreases exponentially in a ' pyramid shape ' .
heading: Introduction

text: After converting discrete text to continuous representation , the DPCNN architecture simply alternates a convolution block and a downsampling layer over and over 1 , leading to a deep network in which internal data size ( as well as per-layer computation ) shrinks in a pyramid shape .
heading: Introduction

text: The network depth can be treated as a meta-parameter .
heading: Introduction

text: The computational complexity of this network is bounded to be no more than twice that of one convolution block .
heading: Introduction

text: We show that DPCNN with 15 weight layers outperforms the previous best models on six benchmark datasets for sentiment classification and topic classification ..
heading: Introduction

text: The first layer performs text region embedding , which generalizes commonly used word embedding to the embedding of text regions covering one or more words .
heading: Introduction

text: It is followed by stacking of convolution blocks ( two convolution layers and a shortcut ) interleaved with pooling layers with stride 2 for downsampling .
heading: Introduction

text: The final pooling layer aggregates internal data for each document into one vector .
heading: Introduction

text: We use max pooling for all pooling layers .

text: ADVERSARIAL TRAINING METHODS FOR SEMI - SUPERVISED TEXT CLASSIFICATION
Previous work has primarily applied adversarial and virtual adversarial training to image classification tasks .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: In this work , we extend these techniques to text classification tasks and sequence models .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Adversarial perturbations typically consist of making small modifications to very many real - valued inputs .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: For text classification , the input is discrete , and usually represented as a series of highdimensional one - hot vectors .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Because the set of high - dimensional one - hot vectors does not admit infinitesimal perturbation , we define the perturbation on continuous word embeddings instead of discrete word inputs .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: We thus propose this approach exclusively as a means of regularizing a text classifier by stabilizing the classification function .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: All experiments used TensorFlow on GPUs .
heading: EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS

text: Code will be available at https://github.com/tensorflow/models/tree/master/adversarial_text .
heading: EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS

text: We trained for 100,000 steps .
heading: EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS

text: We applied gradient clipping with norm set to 1.0 on all the parameters except word embeddings .
heading: EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS

text: For regularization of the recurrent language model , we applied dropout on the word embedding layer with 0.5 dropout rate .
heading: EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS

text: For the bidirectional LSTM model , we used 512 hidden units LSTM for both the standard order and reversed order sequences , and we used 256 dimensional word embeddings which are shared with both of the LSTMs .
heading: EXPERIMENTAL SETTINGS

text: We saw that cosine distance on adversarial and virtual adversarial training ( 0.159-0.331 ) were much smaller than ones on the baseline and random perturbation method ( 0.244-0.399 ) .

text: A C - LSTM Neural Network for Text Classification
In this paper , we introduce a new architecture short for C - LSTM by combining CNN and LSTM to model sentences .
heading: Introduction

text: To benefit from the advantages of both CNN and RNN , we design a simple end - to - end , unified architecture by feeding the output of a one - layer CNN into LSTM .
heading: Introduction

text: The CNN is constructed on top of the pre-trained word vectors from massive unlabeled text data to learn higher - level representions of n-grams .
heading: Introduction

text: Then to learn sequential correlations from higher - level suqence representations , the feature maps of CNN are organized as sequential window features to serve as the input of LSTM .
heading: Introduction

text: We choose sequence - based input other than relying on the syntactic parse trees before feeding in the neural network , thus our model does n't rely on any external language knowledge and complicated pre-processing .
heading: Introduction

text: We implement our model based on Theano ) - a python library , which supports efficient symbolic differentiation and transparent use of a GPU .
heading: Experimental Settings

text: To benefit from the efficiency of parallel computation of the tensors , we train the model on a GPU .

text: Joint Embedding of Words and Labels for Text Classification

Our primary contribution is therefore to propose such a solution by making use of the label embedding framework , and propose the Label - Embedding Attentive Model ( LEAM ) to improve text classification .
heading: Our Contribution

text: The proposed LEAM is implemented by jointly embedding the word and label in the same latent space , and the text representations are constructed directly using the text - label compatibility .
heading: Our Contribution

text: Our label embedding framework has the following salutary properties : ( i ) Label - attentive text representation is informative for the downstream classification task , as it directly learns from a shared joint space , whereas traditional methods proceed in multiple steps by solving intermediate problems .
heading: Our Contribution

text: ( ii ) The LEAM learning procedure only involves a series of basic algebraic operations , and hence it retains the interpretability of simple models , especially when the label description is available .
heading: Our Contribution

text: Setup We use 300 - dimensional Glo Ve word embeddings as initialization for word embeddings and label embeddings in our model .
heading: Experimental Results

text: The final classifier is implemented as an MLP layer followed by a sigmoid or softmax function depending on specific task .
heading: Experimental Results

text: We train our model 's parameters with the Adam Optimizer ( Kingma and Ba , 2014 ) , with an initial learning rate of 0.001 , and a minibatch size of 100 .
heading: Experimental Results

text: Dropout regularization is employed on the final MLP layer , with dropout rate 0.5 .
heading: Experimental Results

text: The model is implemented using Tensorflow and is trained on GPU Titan X .

heading: Experimental Results

text: We compare against the three baselines : a logistic regression model with bag - ofwords , a bidirectional gated recurrent unit ( Bi - GRU ) and a single - layer 1 D convolutional network .
heading: Results

text: We also compare with three recent methods for multi-label classification of clinical text , including Condensed Memory Networks ( C - MemNN ) , Attentive LSTM and Convolutional Attention ( CAML ) .
heading: Results

text: Explicit Interaction Model towards Text Classification

To address the aforementioned problems , we introduce the interaction mechanism ( Wang and Jiang 2016 b ) , which is capable of incorporating the word - level matching signals for text classification .
heading: Introduction

text: Based upon the interaction mechanism , we devise an EXplicit interAction Model ( dubbed as EXAM ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Specifically , the proposed framework consists of three main components : word - level encoder , interaction layer , and aggregation layer .
heading: Introduction

text: The word - level encoder projects the textual contents into the word - level representations .
heading: Introduction

text: Hereafter , the interaction layer calculates the matching scores between the words and classes ( i.e. , constructs the interaction matrix ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Then , the last layer aggregates those matching scores into predictions over each class , respectively .
heading: Introduction

text: Pre-training of Deep Contextualized Embeddings of Words and Entities for Named Entity Disambiguation
heading: title

text: In this paper , we propose a new contextualized embedding model of words and entities for named entity disambiguation ( NED ) .
heading: abstract

text: We evaluated our model by addressing NED using a simple NED model based on the trained contextualized embeddings .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we describe a new contextualized embedding model for words and entities for NED .
heading: Introduction

text: Following , the proposed model is based on the bidirectional transformer encoder .
heading: Introduction

text: It takes a sequence of words and entities in the input text , and produces a contextualized embedding for each word and entity .
heading: Introduction

text: Inspired by MLM , we propose masked entity prediction , a new task that aims to train the embedding model by predicting randomly masked entities based on words and non-masked entities in the input text .
heading: Introduction

text: We trained the model using texts and their entity annotations retrieved from Wikipedia .
heading: Introduction

text: As shown , our models outperformed all previously proposed models .
heading: Results

text: Furthermore , using pseudo entity annotations boosted the accuracy by 0.3 % .
heading: Results

text: Our models achieved new state - of - the - art results on four of the five datasets , namely MSNBC , AQUAINT , ACE2004 , and WNED - WIKI , and performed competitive on the WNED - CLUEWEB dataset .
heading: Methods

text: Furthermore , using pseudo entity annotations improved the performance on the AQUAINT and ACE2004 datasets .
heading: Methods

text: Deep contextualized word representations

We introduce a new type of deep contextualized word representation that models both ( 1 ) complex characteristics of word use ( e.g. , syntax and semantics ) , and ( 2 ) how these uses vary across linguistic contexts ( i.e. , to model polysemy ) .
heading: abstract

text: Pre-trained word representations are a key component in many neural language understanding models .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper , we introduce a new type of deep contextualized word representation that directly addresses both challenges , can be easily integrated into existing models , and significantly improves the state of the art in every considered case across a range of challenging language understanding problems .
heading: Introduction

text: Our representations differ from traditional word type embeddings in that each token is assigned a representation that is a function of the entire input sentence .
heading: Introduction

text: We use vectors derived from a bidirectional LSTM that is trained with a coupled lan - guage model ( LM ) objective on a large text corpus .
heading: Introduction

text: For this reason , we call them ELMo ( Embeddings from Language Models ) representations .
heading: Introduction

text: Unlike previous approaches for learning contextualized word vectors , ELMo representations are deep , in the sense that they are a function of all of the internal layers of the biLM .
heading: Introduction

text: More specifically , we learn a linear combination of the vectors stacked above each input word for each end task , which markedly improves performance over just using the top LSTM layer .
heading: Introduction

text: Using intrinsic evaluations , we show that the higher - level LSTM states capture context - dependent aspects of word meaning ( e.g. , they can be used without modification to perform well on supervised word sense disambiguation tasks ) while lowerlevel states model aspects of syntax ( e.g. , they can be used to do part - of - speech tagging ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Question answering

After adding ELMo to the baseline model , test set F 1 improved by 4.7 % from 81.1 % to 85.8 % , a 24.9 % relative error reduction over the baseline , and improving the overall single model state - of - the - art by 1.4 % .
heading: Question answering

text: The increase of 4.7 % with ELMo is also significantly larger then the 1.8 % improvement from adding CoVe to a baseline model .
heading: Question answering

text: Textual entailment
Overall , adding ELMo to the ESIM model improves accuracy by an average of 0.7 % across five random seeds .
heading: Textual entailment

text: Semantic role labeling

In our experiments with the OntoNotes coreference annotations from the CoNLL 2012 shared task , adding ELMo improved the average F 1 by 3.2 % from 67.2 to 70.4 , establishing a new state of the art , again improving over the previous best ensemble result by 1.6 % F 1 .
heading: Semantic role labeling

text: Named entity extraction
As shown in , our ELMo enhanced biLSTM - CRF achieves 92. 22 % F 1 averaged over five runs .
heading: Named entity extraction

text: Sense Vocabulary Compression through the Semantic Knowledge of WordNet for Neural Word Sense Disambiguation
heading: title

text: We propose two different methods that greatly reduce the size of neural WSD models , with the benefit of improving their coverage without additional training data , and without impacting their precision .
heading: abstract

text: In addition to our methods , we present a WSD system which relies on pre-trained BERT word vectors in order to achieve results that significantly outperforms the state of the art on all WSD evaluation tasks .
heading: abstract

text: Word Sense Disambiguation ( WSD ) is a task which aims to clarify a text by assigning to each of its words the most suitable sense labels , given a predefined sense inventory .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , the idea is to solve this issue by taking advantage of the semantic relationships between senses included in WordNet , such as the hypernymy , the hyponymy , the meronymy , the antonymy , etc .
heading: Introduction

text: Our method is based on the observation that a sense and its closest related senses ( it s hypernym or it s hyponyms for instance ) all share a common idea or concept , and so a word can sometimes be disambiguated using only related concepts .
heading: Introduction

text: For BERT , we used the model named " bert - largecased " of the PyTorch implementation 3 , which consists of vectors of dimension 1024 , trained on Book s Corpus and English Wikipedia .
heading: Implementation details

text: For the Transformer encoder layers , we used the same parameters as the " base " model of , that is 6 layers with 8 attention heads , a hidden size of 2048 , and a dropout of 0.1 .
heading: Implementation details

text: In the results in , we first observe that our systems that use the sense vocabulary compression through hypernyms or through all relations obtain scores that are overall equivalent to the systems that do not use it .
heading: Evaluation

text: In comparison to the other works , thanks to the Princeton WordNet Gloss Corpus added to the training data and the use of BERT as input embeddings , we outperform systematically the state of the art on every task .
heading: Evaluation

text: As we can see in , the additional training corpus ( WNGC ) and even more the use of BERT as input embeddings both have a major impact on our results and lead to scores above the state of the art .
heading: Ablation Study

text: Using BERT instead of ELMo or Glo Ve improves respectively the score by approximately 3 and 5 points in every experiment , and adding the WNGC to the training data improves it by approximately 2 points .
heading: Ablation Study

text: Finally , using ensembles adds roughly another 1 point to the final F1 score .
heading: Ablation Study

text: However , the compression method through all relations seems to negatively impact the results in some cases ( when using ELMo or GloVe especially ) .
heading: Ablation Study

text: Incorporating Glosses into Neural Word Sense Disambiguation
heading: title

text: Word Sense Disambiguation ( WSD ) aims to identify the correct meaning of polysemous words in the particular context .

text: In this paper , we propose a novel model GAS : a gloss - augmented WSD neural network which is a variant of the memory network .
heading: There are several lines of research on WSD .

text: GAS jointly encodes the context and glosses of the target word and models the semantic relationship between the context and glosses in the memory module .
heading: There are several lines of research on WSD .

text: In order to measure the inner relationship between glosses and context more accurately , we employ multiple passes operation within the memory as the re-reading process and adopt two memory updating mechanisms .

text: Word Sense Disambiguation using a Bidirectional LSTM
heading: title

text: The task of assigning a word token in a text , e.g. rock , to a well defined word sense in a lexicon is called word sense disambiguation ( WSD ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Improved WSD would be beneficial to many natural language processing ( NLP ) problems , e.g. machine translation , information Retrieval , information Extraction , and sense aware word representations .
heading: Introduction

text: We aim to mitigate these problems by ( 1 ) modeling the sequence of words surrounding the target word , and ( 2 ) refrain from using any hand crafted features or external resources and instead represent the words using real valued vector representation , i.e. word embeddings .
heading: Introduction

text: The source code , implemented using TensorFlow , has been released as open source 1 .
heading: Experimental settings

text: The embeddings are initialized using a set of freely available 2 Glo Ve vectors trained on Wikipedia and Gigaword .
heading: Embeddings

text: Words not included in this set are initialized from N ( 0 , 0.1 ) .
heading: Embeddings

text: Our proposed model achieves the top score on SE2 and are tied with IMS + adapted CW on SE3 .
heading: Results

text: Moreover , we see that dropword consistently improves the results on both SE2 and SE3 .
heading: Results

text: Randomizing the order of the input words yields a substantially worse result , which provides evidence for our hypothesis that the order of the words are significant .
heading: Results

text: We also see that the system effectively makes use of the information in the pre-trained word embeddings and that they are essential to the performance of our system on these datasets .
heading: Results

text: Knowledge - based Word Sense Disambiguation using Topic Models
heading: title

text: Disambiguation is an open problem in Natural Language Processing which is particularly challenging and useful in the unsupervised setting where all the words in any given text need to be disambiguated without using any labeled data .
heading: abstract

text: Typically WSD systems use the sentence or a small window of words around the target word as the context for disambiguation because their computational complexity scales exponentially with the size of the context .
heading: abstract

text: Word Sense Disambiguation ( WSD ) is the task of mapping an ambiguous word in a given context to its correct meaning .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper , we propose a novel knowledge - based WSD algorithm for the all - word WSD task , which utilizes the whole document as the context for a word , rather than just the current sentence used by most WSD systems .
heading: Introduction

text: In order to model the whole document for WSD , we leverage the formalism of topic models , especially Latent Dirichlet Allocation ( LDA ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Our method is a variant of LDA in which the topic proportions for a document are replaced by synset proportions for a document .
heading: Introduction

text: We use a non-uniform prior for the synset distribution over words to model the frequency of words within a synset .
heading: Introduction

text: Furthermore , we also model the relationships between synsets by using a logisticnormal prior for drawing the synset proportions of the document .
heading: Introduction

text: The proposed method , denoted by WSD - TM in the tables referring to WSD using topic models , outperforms the state - of - the - art WSD system by a significant margin ( pvalue < 0.01 ) by achieving an overall F1 - score of 66.9 as compared to Moro14 's score of 65.5 .
heading: Experiments & Results

text: We also observe that the performance of the proposed model is not much worse than the best supervised system , Melamud16 ( 69.4 ) .
heading: Experiments & Results

text: The proposed system outperforms all previous knowledgebased systems overall parts of speech .
heading: Experiments & Results

text: Mixing Context Granularities for Improved Entity Linking on Question Answering Data across Entity Categories
heading: title

text: The first stage for every QA approach is entity linking ( EL ) , that is the identification of entity mentions in the question and linking them to entities in KB .
heading: Introduction

text: The state - of - the - art QA systems usually rely on off - the - shelf EL systems to extract entities from the question .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper , we present an approach that tackles the challenges listed above : we perform entity mention detection and entity disambiguation jointly in a single neural model that makes the whole process end - to - end differentiable .
heading: PERFORMER

text: To overcome the noise in the data , we automatically learn features over a set of contexts of different granularity levels .
heading: PERFORMER

text: Each level of granularity is handled by a separate component of the model .
heading: PERFORMER

text: A token - level component extracts higher - level features from the whole question context , whereas a character - level component builds lower - level features for the candidate n-gram .
heading: PERFORMER

text: Simultaneously , we extract features from the knowledge base context of the candidate entity : character - level features are extracted for the entity label and higher - level features are produced based on the entities surrounding the candidate entity in the knowledge graph .
heading: PERFORMER

text: This information is aggregated and used to predict whether the n-gram is an entity mention and to what entity it should be linked .
heading: PERFORMER

text: The complete code as well as the scripts that produce the evaluation data can be found here : https://github.com/UKPLab/ starsem2018-entity-linking .
heading: Code and datasets

text: Existing systems
In our experiments , we compare to DBPedia Spotlight that was used in several QA systems and represents a strong baseline for entity linking 4 .
heading: Existing systems

text: In addition , we are able to compare to the state - of - the - art S - MART system , since their output on the WebQSP datasets was publicly released 5 .
heading: Existing systems

text: We also include a heuristics baseline that ranks candidate entities according to their frequency in Wikipedia .
heading: Existing systems

text: Simplified VCG

In particular , we employ features that cover ( 1 ) frequency of the entity in Wikipedia , ( 2 ) edit distance between the label of the entity and the token n-gram , ( 3 ) number of entities and relations immediately connected to the entity in the KB , ( 4 ) word overlap between the input question and the labels of the connected entities and relations , ( 5 ) length of the n-gram .
heading: Simplified VCG

text: The VCG model shows the overall F- score result that is better than the DBPedia Spotlight baseline by a wide margin .
heading: Results

text: It is notable that again our model achieves higher precision values as compared to other approaches and manages to keep a satisfactory level of recall .
heading: Results

text: One Single Deep Bidirectional LSTM Network for Word Sense Disambiguation of Text Data
heading: title

text: To mine these data properly , attributable to their innate ambiguity , a Word Sense Disambiguation ( WSD ) algorithm can avoid numbers of difficulties in Natural Language Processing ( NLP ) pipeline .
heading: abstract

text: However , considering a large number of ambiguous words in one language or technical domain , we may encounter limiting constraints for proper deployment of existing WSD models .
heading: abstract

text: In this effort , we develop our supervised WSD model that leverages a Bidirectional Long Short - Term Memory ( BLSTM ) network .
heading: Introduction

text: This network works with neural sense vectors ( i.e. sense embeddings ) , which are learned during model training , and employs neural word vectors ( i.e. word embeddings ) , which are learned through an unsupervised deep learning approach called GloVe ( Global Vectors for word representation ) for the context words .

text: Neural Sequence Learning Models for Word Sense Disambiguation
As one of the long - standing challenges in Natural Language Processing ( NLP ) , Word Sense Disambiguation , WSD ) has received considerable attention over recent years .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper our focus is on supervised WSD , but we depart from previous approaches and adopt a different perspective on the task : instead of framing a separate classification problem for each given word , we aim at modeling the joint disambiguation of the target text as a whole in terms of a sequence labeling problem .
heading: Introduction

text: With this in mind , we design , analyze and compare experimentally various neural architectures of different complexities , ranging from a single bidirectional Long Short - Term Memory to a sequence - tosequence approach .
heading: Introduction

text: Each architecture reflects a particular way of modeling the disambiguation problem , but they all share some key features that set them apart from previous supervised approaches to WSD : they are trained end - to - end from sense - annotated text to sense labels , and learn a single all - words model from the training data , without fine tuning or explicit engineering of local features .
heading: Introduction

text: To set a level playing field with comparison systems on English all - words WSD , we followed and , for all our models , we used a layer of word embeddings pre-trained 8 on the English uk WaC corpus as initialization , and kept them fixed during the training process .
heading: Architecture Details .

text: For all architectures we then employed 2 layers of bidirectional LSTM with 2048 hidden units ( 1024 units per direction ) .
heading: Architecture Details .

text: We report the F1 - score on each in - dividual test set , as well as the F1- score obtained on the concatenation of all four test sets , divided by part - of - speech tag .
heading: Experimental Results

text: As supervised systems , we considered Context2 Vec and It Makes Sense , both the original implementation and the best configuration reported by , which also integrates word embeddings using exponential decay .
heading: Experimental Results

text: 11 Overall , both BLSTM and Seq2Seq achieved results that are either state - of - the - art or statistically equivalent ( unpaired t- test , p < 0.05 ) to the best supervised system in each benchmark , performing on par with word experts tuned over explicitly engineered features .
heading: Experimental Results

text: Interestingly enough , BLSTM models tended consistently to outperform their Seq2Seq counterparts , suggesting that an encoder - decoder architecture , despite being more powerful , might be suboptimal for WSD .
heading: Experimental Results

text: English All - words WSD
heading: Experimental Results

text: It is worth noting that RNN - based architectures outperformed classical supervised approaches when dealing with verbs , which are shown to be highly ambiguous .
heading: Experimental Results

text: Both BLSTM and Seq2Seq outperformed UKB and IMS trained on SemCor , as well as recent supervised approaches based on distributional semantics and neural architectures .
heading: Experimental Results

text: Multilingual All - words WSD
heading: Experimental Results

text: F - score figures show that bilingual and multilingual models , despite being trained only on English data , consistently outperformed the MFS baseline and achieved results that are competitive with the best participating systems in the task .
heading: Experimental Results

text: We also note that the overall F- score performance did not change substantially ( and slightly improved ) when moving from bilingual to multilingual models , despite the increase in the number of target languages treated simultaneously .

text: Learning Distributed Representations of Texts and Entities from Knowledge Base
heading: title

text: In particular , we propose Neural Text - Entity Encoder ( NTEE ) , a neural network model to jointly learn distributed representations of texts ( i.e. , sentences and paragraphs ) and KB entities .
heading: Introduction

text: For every text in the KB , our model aims to predict its relevant entities , and places the text and the relevant entities close to each other in a continuous vector space .
heading: Introduction

text: We use humanedited entity annotations obtained from Wikipedia ( see ) as supervised data of relevant entities to the texts containing these annotations .
heading: Introduction

text: Note that , KB entities have been conventionally used to model semantics of texts .
heading: Introduction

text: A representative example is Explicit Semantic Analysis ( ESA ) , which represents the semantics of a text using a sparse vector space , where each dimension corresponds to the relevance score of the text to each entity .
heading: Introduction

text: Essentially , ESA shows that text can be accurately represented using a small set of its relevant entities .
heading: Introduction

text: Furthermore , we also consider that placing texts and entities into the same vector space enables us to easily compute the similarity between texts and entities , which can be beneficial for various KB - related tasks .
heading: Introduction

text: We release our code and trained models to the community at https://github.com/ studio-ousia /ntee to facilitate further academic research .
heading: Introduction

text: BOW is a conventional approach using a logistic regression ( LR ) classifier trained with binary BOW features to predict the correct answer .
heading: Baselines

text: BOW - DT is based on the BOW baseline augmented with the feature set with dependency relation indicators .
heading: Baselines

text: QANTA is an approach based on a recursive neural network to derive the distributed representations of questions .
heading: Baselines

text: FTS - BRNN is based on the bidirectional recurrent neural network ( RNN ) with gated recurrent units ( GRU ) .
heading: Baselines

text: In particular , despite the simplicity of the neural network architecture of our method compared to the state - of - the - art methods ( i.e. , QANTA and FTS - BRNN ) , our method clearly outperformed these methods .
heading: Results

text: Our observations indicated that our method mostly performed perfect in terms of predicting the types of target answers ( e.g. , locations , events , and people ) .
heading: Results

text: Joint Learning of the Embedding of Words and Entities for Named Entity Disambiguation
heading: title

text: Named Entity Disambiguation ( NED ) refers to the task of resolving multiple named entity mentions in a document to their correct references in a knowledge base ( KB ) ( e.g. , Wikipedia ) .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we propose a novel embedding method specifically designed for NED .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we propose a method to construct a novel embedding that jointly maps words and entities into the same continuous vector space .
heading: Introduction

text: In this model , similar words and entities are placed close to one another in a vector space .
heading: Introduction

text: Hence , we can measure the similarity between any pair of items ( i.e. , words , entities , and a word and an entity ) by simply computing their cosine similarity .
heading: Introduction

text: Our model is based on the skip - gram model , a recently proposed embedding model that learns to predict each context word given the target word .
heading: Introduction

text: Our model consists of the following three models based on the skip - gram model :
heading: Introduction

text: 1 ) the conventional skip - gram model that learns to predict neighboring words given the target word in text corpora , 2 ) the KB graph model that learns to estimate neighboring entities given the target entity in the link graph of the KB , and 3 ) the anchor context model that learns to predict neighboring words given the target entity using anchors and their context words in the KB .
heading: Introduction

text: Based on our proposed embedding , we also develop a straightforward NED method that computes two contexts using the proposed embedding : textual context similarity , and coherence .
heading: Introduction

text: Our NED method combines these contexts with several standard features ( e.g. , prior probability ) using supervised machine learning .
heading: Introduction

text: Our method successfully achieved enhanced performance on both the CoNLL and the TAC 2010 datasets .
heading: CoNLL

text: Moreover , we found that the choice of candidate generation method considerably affected performance on the CoNLL dataset .
heading: CoNLL

text: Our method outperformed all the state - of - the - art methods on both datasets .
heading: CoNLL

text: 3D Morphable Models ( 3 DMMs ) are powerful statistical models of 3D facial shape and texture , and among the stateof - the - art methods for reconstructing facial shape from single images .
heading: abstract

text: 3 D facial shape estimation from single images has attracted the attention of many researchers the past twenty years .
heading: Introduction

text: We propose a methodology for learning a statistical texture model from " in - the -wild " facial images , which is in full correspondence with a statistical shape prior that exhibits both identity and expression variations .
heading: Introduction

text: Motivated by the success of feature - based ( e.g. , HOG , SIFT ) Active Appearance Models ( AAMs ) we further show how to learn featurebased texture models for 3 DMMs .
heading: Introduction

text: We show that the advantage of using the " in - the -wild " feature - based texture model is that the fitting strategy gets simplified since there is not need to optimize with respect to the illumination parameters .
heading: Introduction

text: Unsupervised Training for 3D Morphable Model Regression
This paper presents a method for training a regression network that removes both the need for supervised training data and the reliance on inverse rendering to reproduce image pixels .
heading: Introduction

text: Instead , the network learns to minimize a loss based on the facial identity features produced by a face recognition network such as VGG - Face or Google 's FaceNet .
heading: Introduction

text: We exploit this invariance to apply a loss that matches the identity features between the input photograph and a synthetic rendering of the predicted face .
heading: Introduction

text: We alleviate the fooling problem by applying three novel losses : a batch distribution loss to match the statistics of each training batch to the statistics of the morphable model , a loopback loss to ensure the regression network can correctly reinterpret its own output , and a multi-view identity loss that combines features from multiple , independent views of the predicted shape .
heading: Introduction

text: Using this scheme , we train a 3D shape and texture regression network using only a face recognition network , a morphable face model , and a dataset of unlabeled face images .
heading: Introduction

text: We show that despite learning from unlabeled photographs , the 3D face results improve on the accuracy of previous work and are often recognizable as the original subjects .
heading: Introduction

text: We demonstrate the superior representation power of our nonlinear 3 DMM over its linear counterpart , and its contribution to face alignment and 3D reconstruction .
heading: abstract

text: Hence , we utilize two network decoders , instead of two PCA spaces , as the shape and texture model components , respectively .
heading: Introduction

text: With careful consideration of each component , we design different networks for shape and texture : the multi - layer perceptron ( MLP ) for shape and convolutional neural network ( CNN ) for texture .
heading: Introduction

text: Each decoder will take a shape or texture representation as input and output the dense 3 D face or a face texture .
heading: Introduction

text: Further , we learn the fitting algorithm to our nonlinear 3 DMM , which is formulated as a CNN encoder .
heading: Introduction

text: The encoder takes a 2 D face image as input and generates the shape and texture parameters , from which two decoders estimate the 3D face and texture .
heading: Introduction

text: The 3 D face and texture would perfectly reconstruct the input face , if the fitting algorithm and 3 DMM are well learnt .
heading: Introduction

text: Therefore , we design a differentiable rendering layer to generate a reconstructed face by fusing the 3D face , texture , and the camera projection parameters estimated by the encoder .
heading: Introduction

text: Finally , the endto - end learning scheme is constructed where the encoder and two decoders are learnt jointly to minimize the difference between the reconstructed face and the input face .
heading: Introduction

text: Jointly learning the 3 DMM and the model fitting encoder allows us to leverage the large collection of unconstrained 2D images without relying on 3D scans .
heading: Introduction

text: We show significantly improved shape and texture representation power over the linear 3 DMM .

text: Face Alignment Across Large Poses : A 3D Solution
Face alignment , which fits a face model to an image and extracts the semantic meanings of facial pixels , has been an important topic in CV community .
heading: abstract

text: poses , we propose to fit the 3D dense face model rather than the sparse landmark shape model to the image .
heading: Introduction

text: We call this method 3D Dense Face Alignment ( 3DDFA ) .
heading: Introduction

text: To resolve the fitting process in 3 DDFA , we propose a cascaded convolutional neutral network ( CNN ) based regression method .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , we adopt CNN to fit the 3D face model with a specifically designed feature , namely Projected Normalized Coordinate Code ( PNCC ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Besides , Weighted Parameter Distance Cost ( WPDC ) is proposed as the cost function .
heading: Introduction

text: To the best of our knowledge , this is the first attempt to solve the 3D face alignment with CNN .
heading: Introduction

text: To enable the training of the 3DDFA , we construct a face database containing pairs of 2D face images and 3D face models .
heading: Introduction

text: We further propose a face profiling algorithm to synthesize 60 k + training samples across large poses .
heading: Introduction

text: The synthesized samples well simulate the face appearances in large poses and boost the performance of both prior and our proposed face alignment algorithms .
heading: Introduction

text: The database , face profiling code and 3 DDFA code are released at http://www.cbsr.ia.ac.cn/users / xiangyuzhu/ .
heading: Introduction

text: To this end , we propose a new framework to augment training for facial landmark detection without using extra knowledge .
heading: Introduction

text: Instead of directly generating images , we first map face images into the space of structure and style .
heading: Introduction

text: To guarantee the disentanglement of these two spaces , we design a conditional variational auto - encoder model , in which Kullback - Leiber ( KL ) divergence loss and skip connections are incorporated for compact representation of style and structure respectively .

text: Deep Alignment Network : A convolutional neural network for robust face alignment
heading: title

text: The goal of face alignment is to localize a set of predefined facial landmarks ( eye corners , mouth corners etc. ) in an image of a face .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , we address the above shortcoming by proposing a novel face alignment method which we dub Deep Alignment Network ( DAN ) .
heading: Introduction

text: It is based on a multistage neural network where each stage refines the landmark positions estimated at the previous stage , iteratively improving the landmark locations .
heading: Introduction

text: The input to each stage of our algorithm ( except the first stage ) area face image normalized to a canonical pose and an image learned from the dense layer of the previous stage .
heading: Introduction

text: To make use of the entire face image during the process of face alignment , we additionally input at each stage a landmark heatmap , which is a key element of our system .
heading: Introduction

text: During data augmentation a total of 10 images are created from each input image in the training set .
heading: Implementation

text: Training is performed using Theano 0.9.0 and Lasagne 0.2 .
heading: Implementation

text: For optimization we use Adam stochastic optimization with an initial step size of 0.001 and mini batch size of 64 .
heading: Implementation

text: For validation we use a random subset of 100 images from the training set .

text: DeCaFA : Deep Convolutional Cascade for Face Alignment In The Wild
heading: title

text: Face Alignment is an active computer vision domain , that consists in localizing a number of facial landmarks that vary across datasets .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we introduce a Deep convolutional Cascade for Face Alignment ( DeCaFA ) .
heading: Introduction

text: DeCaFA is composed of several stages that each produce landmark - wise attention maps , relatively to heterogeneous annotation markups .
heading: Introduction

text: It illustrates how these attention maps are refined through the successive stages , and how the different prediction tasks can benefit from each other .
heading: Introduction

text: The DeCaFA models that will be investigated below use 1 to 4 stages that each contains 12 3 3 convolutional layers with 64 ? 64 ? 128 ? 128 ? 256 ? 256 channels for the downsampling portion , and vice - versa for the upsampling portion .
heading: Implementation details

text: The input images are resized to 128 128 grayscale images prior to being processed by the network .
heading: Implementation details

text: Each convolution is followed by a batch normalization layer with ReLU activation .
heading: Implementation details

text: In order to generate smooth feature maps we do not use transposed convolution but bilinear image upsampling followed with 3 3 convolutional layers .
heading: Implementation details

text: The whole architecture is trained using ADAM optimizer with a 5e ? 4 learning rate with momentum 0.9 and learning rate annealing with power 0.9 .
heading: Implementation details

text: We apply 400000 updates with batch size 8 for each database , with alternating updates between the databases .
heading: Implementation details

text: The accuracy steadily increases as we add more stages , and saturates after the third on LFPW and HELEN , which is a well - known behavior of cascaded models , showing that DeCaFA with weighted intermediate supervision indeed works as a cascade , by first providing coarse estimates and refining in the later stages .
heading: Ablation study

text: Coarsely annotated data ( 5 landmarks ) significantly helps the fine - grained landmark localization , as it is integrated a kind of weakly supervised scheme .
heading: Ablation study

text: First , reinjecting the whole input image ( F 3 - Equation vs F 2 - Equation ) significantly improves the accuracy on challenging data such as 300 W - challenging or WFLW - pose , where the first cascade stages may commit errors .
heading: Ablation study

text: F 4 - Equation ( 7 ) and F 3 fusion ( cascaded models ) using local + global information rivals the basic deep approach F 1 - Equation ( 4 ) .
heading: Ablation study

text: Furthermore , F 5 - Equation fusion , which uses local and global cues is the best by a significant margin .
heading: Ablation study

text: Furthermore , chaining the transfer layers is better than using independant transfer layers : likewise , in such a case , the first transfer layer benefits from the gradients from the subsequents layer at train time .
heading: Ablation study

text: Finally , shows a comparison of our method and state - of - the - art approaches on Celeb A .
heading: Ablation study

text: Overall , DeCaFA sets a new state - of - the - art on the three databases with several evaluation metrics .

heading: Introduction

text: Due to the translation invariance of the convolution operation in bottom - up and top - down CNN structures such as stacked Hourglass ( HG ) , the network is notable to capture coordinate information , which we believe is useful for facial landmark localization , since the structure of human faces is relatively stable .

text: To encode boundary coordinates , we also add a sub-task of boundary prediction by concatenating an additional boundary channel into the ground truth heatmap which is jointly trained with other channels .
