heading: title

text: Dataset and model will be publicly available at https://wywu.github.io/projects/LAB/LAB.html
Face alignment , which refers to facial landmark detection in this work , serves as a key step for many face applications , e.g. , face recognition , face verification and face frontalisation .
heading: Introduction

text: To this end , we use well - defined facial boundaries to represent the geometric structure of the human face .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , we represent facial structure using 13 boundary lines .
heading: Introduction

text: Our boundary - aware face alignment algorithm contains two stages .
heading: Introduction

text: We first estimate facial boundary heatmaps and then regress landmarks with the help of boundary heatmaps .
heading: Introduction

text: To explore the relationship between facial boundaries and landmarks , we introduce adversarial learning ideas by using a landmark - based boundary effectiveness discriminator .
heading: Introduction

text: The boundary heatmap estimator , landmark regressor , and boundary effectiveness discriminator can be jointly learned in an end - to - end manner .
heading: Introduction

text: We used stacked hourglass structure to estimate facial boundary heatmap and model the structure between facial boundaries through message passing to increase its robustness to occlusion .
heading: Introduction

text: The boundary heatmaps serve as structure cue to guide feature learning for the landmark regressor .
heading: Introduction

text: Joint 3D Face Reconstruction and Dense Face Alignment from A Single Image with 2D - Assisted Self - Supervised Learning
heading: title

text: 3 D face reconstruction from a single 2D image is a challenging problem with broad applications .
heading: Best viewed in color .

text: 3 D face reconstruction from a single 2D image is a challenging problem with broad applications .
heading: Abstract

text: 3 D face reconstruction is an important task in the field of computer vision and graphics .
heading: Introduction

text: In order to overcome the intrinsic limitation of existing 3 D face recovery models , we propose a novel learning method that leverages 2D " in - the - wild " face images to effectively supervise and facilitate the 3D face model learning .
heading: Introduction

text: We design a novel self - supervised learning method that is able to train a 3 D face model with weak supervision from 2D images .
heading: Introduction

text: The model should be able to recover 2D landmarks from predicted 3D ones via direct 3D - to - 2D projection .
heading: Introduction

text: Additionally , our proposed method also exploits cycle - consistency over the 2D landmark predictions , i.e. , taking the recovered 2D landmarks as input , the model should be able to generate 2D landmarks ( by projecting its predicted 3D landmarks ) that have small difference with the annotated ones .
heading: Introduction

heading: title

text: In this paper , we propose a novel Semantic Alignment method which reduces the ' semantic ambiguity ' intrinsi-cally .
heading: The others move to the semantically accurate positions .

text: We model the ' real ' ground - truth as a latent variable to optimize , and the optimized ' real ' ground - truth then supervises the landmark detection network training .
heading: The others move to the semantically accurate positions .

text: Accordingly , we propose a probabilistic model which can simultaneously search the ' real ' ground - truth and train the landmark detection network in an end - to - end way .
heading: The others move to the semantically accurate positions .

text: In this probabilistic model , the prior model is to constrain the latent variable to be close to the observations of the ' real ' ground truth , one of which is the human annotation .
heading: The others move to the semantically accurate positions .

text: The likelihood model is to reduce the Pearson Chi-square distance between the expected and the predicted distributions of ' real ' ground - truth .

text: In this paper , we propose a novel face detection network with three novel contributions that address three key aspects of face detection , including better feature learning , progressive loss design and anchor assign based data augmentation , respectively .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we propose three novel techniques to address the above three issues , respectively .
heading: Loss design

text: First , we introduce a Feature Enhance Module ( FEM ) to enhance the discriminability and robustness of the features , which combines the advantages of the FPN in PyramidBox and Receptive Field Block ( RFB ) in RFBNet .
heading: Loss design

text: Second , motivated by the hierarchical loss and pyramid anchor in PyramidBox , we design Progressive Anchor Loss ( PAL ) that uses progressive anchor sizes for not only different levels , but also different shots .
heading: Loss design

text: Specifically , we assign smaller anchor sizes in the first shot , and use larger sizes in the second shot .
heading: Loss design

text: Third , we propose Improved Anchor Matching ( IAM ) , which integrates anchor partition strategy and anchor-based data augmentation to better match anchors and ground truth faces , and thus provides better initialization for the regressor .
heading: Loss design

text: Besides , since these techniques are all related to two - stream design , we name the proposed network as Dual Shot Face Detector ( DSFD ) .
heading: Loss design

text: During inference , the first shot 's outputs are ignored and the second shot predicts top 5 k high confident detections .

text: A Unified Multi-scale Deep Convolutional Neural Network for Fast Object Detection
heading: title

text: A unified deep neural network , denoted the multi -scale CNN ( MS - CNN ) , is proposed for fast multi-scale object detection .
heading: abstract

text: State - of - the - art object detection performance , at up to 15 fps , is reported on datasets , such as KITTI and Caltech , containing a substantial number of small objects .
heading: abstract

text: This work proposes a unified multi-scale deep CNN , denoted the multi -scale CNN ( MS - CNN ) , for fast object detection .
heading: Introduction

text: Similar to , this network consists of two sub-networks : an object proposal network and an accurate detection network .
heading: Introduction

text: Both of them are learned end - to - end and share computations .
heading: Introduction

text: However , to ease the inconsistency between the sizes of objects and receptive fields , object detection is performed with multiple output layers , each focusing on objects within certain scale ranges ( see ) .
heading: Introduction

text: The complimentary detectors at different output layers are combined to form a strong multi-scale detector .
heading: Introduction

text: The performance of the MS - CNN detector was evaluated on the KITTI and Caltech Pedestrian benchmarks .
heading: Experimental Evaluation

text: The detector was implemented in C ++ within the Caffe toolbox , and source code is available at https://github.com/zhaoweicai/mscnn .
heading: Experimental Evaluation

heading: Experimental Evaluation

heading: Experimental Evaluation

heading: Object Detection Evaluation

text: Region proposal mechanisms are essential for existing deep learning approaches to object detection in images .
heading: abstract

text: Existing deep learning approaches to solve this task ( e.g. , R - CNN and its variants ) mainly rely on region proposal mechanisms ( e.g. , region proposal networks ( RPN s ) ) to generate potential bounding boxes in an image and then classify these bounding boxes to achieve object detection .
heading: Introduction

text: Motivated by this , in this work , we propose a weakly supervised multimodal annotation segmentation ( WSMA - Seg ) approach , which uses segmentation models to achieve an accurate and robust object detection without NMS .
heading: Introduction

text: In the training phase , WSMA - Seg first converts weakly supervised bounding box annotations in detection tasks to multi-channel segmentation - like masks , called multimodal annotations ; then , a segmentation model is trained using multimodal annotations as labels to learn multimodal heatmaps for the training images .
heading: Introduction

text: In the testing phase , the resulting heatmaps of a given test image are converted into an instance - aware segmentation map based on a pixel - level logic operation ; then , a contour tracing operation is conducted to generate contours for objects using the segmentation map ; finally , bounding boxes of objects are created as circumscribed quadrilaterals of their corresponding contours .
heading: Introduction

text: RetinaFace : Single - stage Dense Face Localisation in the Wild
heading: title

text: Though tremendous strides have been made in uncontrolled face detection , accurate and efficient face localisation in the wild remains an open challenge .
heading: abstract

text: Extra annotations and code have been made available at : https://github.com/deepinsight/insightface/tree/master/RetinaFace .
heading: Specifically ,

text: Based on a single - stage design , we propose a novel pixel - wise face localisation method named Reti- naFace , which employs a multi-task learning strategy to simultaneously predict face score , face box , five facial landmarks , and 3D position and correspondence of each facial pixel .
heading: Introduction

text: Training Details .
We train the RetinaFace using SGD optimiser ( momentum at 0.9 , weight decay at 0.0005 , batch size of 8 4 ) on four NVIDIA Tesla P40 ( 24GB ) GPUs .
heading: Training Details .

text: The learning rate starts from 10 ? 3 , rising to 10 ? 2 after 5 epochs , then divided by 10 at 55 and 68 epochs .
heading: Training Details .

text: The training process terminates at 80 epochs .
heading: Training Details .

text: Testing Details .
For testing on WIDER FACE , we follow the standard practices of and employ flip as well as multi-scale ( the short edge of image at [ 500 , 800 , 1100 , 1400 , 1700 ] ) strategies .
heading: Testing Details .

text: Box voting [ 15 ] is applied on the union set of predicted face boxes using an IoU threshold at 0.4 .
heading: Testing Details .

text: Adding the branch of five facial landmark regression significantly improves the face box AP ( 0.408 % ) and mAP ( 0.775 % ) on the Hard subset , suggesting that landmark localisation is crucial for improving the accuracy of face detection .
heading: Ablation Study

text: By contrast , adding the dense regression branch increases the face box AP on Easy and Medium subsets but slightly deteriorates the results on the Hard subset , indicating the difficulty of dense regression under challenging scenarios .
heading: Ablation Study

text: Nevertheless , learning landmark and dense regression jointly enables a further improvement compared to adding landmark regression only .
heading: Ablation Study

More specifically , RetinaFace produces the best AP in all subsets of both validation and test sets , i.e. , 96.9 % ( Easy ) , 96.1 % ( Medium ) and 91.8 % ( Hard ) for validation set , and 96.3 % ( Easy ) , 95.6 % ( Medium ) and 91.4 % ( Hard ) for test set .

text: HyperFace : A Deep Multi-task Learning Framework for Face Detection , Landmark Localization , Pose Estimation , and Gender Recognition
heading: title

text: In this paper , we present a novel framework based on CNNs for simultaneous face detection , facial landmarks localization , head pose estimation and gender recognition from a given image ( see ) .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: We design a CNN architecture to learn common features for these tasks and exploit the synergy among them .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: We refer the set of intermediate layer features as hyperfeatures .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Hence , we construct a separate fusion - CNN to fuse the hyperfeatures .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: In order to learn the tasks , we train them simultaneously using multiple loss functions .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The deep CNN combined with the fusion - CNN can be learned together in an end -toend fashion .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Face Detection
As can be seen from these figures , both HyperFace and HF - ResNet outperform all the reported academic and commercial detectors on the AFW and PASCAL datasets .
heading: Face Detection

text: HyperFace achieves a high mean average precision ( m AP ) of 97.9 % and 92.46 % , for AFW and PASCAL datasets respectively .
heading: Face Detection

text: CMS- RCNN : Contextual Multi- Scale Region - based CNN for Unconstrained Face Detection
heading: title

text: Robust face detection in the wild is one of the ultimate components to support various facial related problems , i.e. unconstrained face recognition , facial periocular recognition , facial landmarking and pose estimation , facial expression recognition , 3 D facial model construction , etc .
heading: abstract

text: Although the face detection problem has been intensely studied for decades with various commercial applications , it still meets problems in some real - world scenarios due to numerous challenges , e.g. heavy facial occlusions , extremely low resolutions , strong illumination , exceptionally pose variations , image or video compression artifacts , etc .
heading: abstract

text: This paper presents an advanced CNN based approach named Contextual Multi - Scale Region - based CNN ( CMS - RCNN ) to handle the problem of face detection in digital face images collected under numerous challenging conditions , e.g. heavy facial occlusion , illumination , extreme offangle , low - resolution , scale difference , etc .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Our designed region - based CNN architecture allows the network to simultaneously look at multi-scale features , as well as to explicitly look outside facial regions as the potential body regions .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Additionally this architecture also helps to synchronize both the global semantic features in high level layers and the localization features in low level layers for facial representation .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Our CMS - RCNN method introduces the Multi - Scale Region Proposal Network ( MS - RPN ) to generate a set of region candidates and the Contextual Multi - Scale Convolution Neural Network ( CMS - CNN ) to do inference on the region candidates of facial regions .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Our CMS - RCNN is implemented in the Caffe deep learning framework .
heading: Implementation Details

text: The first 5 sets of convolution layers have the same architecture as the deep VGG - 16 model , and during training their parameters are initialized from the pre-trained VGG - 16 .
heading: Implementation Details

text: In the MS - RPN , we want ' conv3 ' , ' conv4 ' , and ' conv5 ' to be synchronized to the same size so that concatenation can be applied .
heading: Implementation Details

text: So ' conv3 ' is followed by pooling layer to perform down - sampling .
heading: Implementation Details

text: Then ' conv3 ' , ' conv4 ' , and ' conv5 ' are normalized along the channel axis to a learnable re-weighting scale and concatenated together .
heading: Implementation Details

text: To ensure training convergence , the initial re-weighting scale needs to be carefully set .
heading: Implementation Details

text: Here we set the initial scale of ' conv3 ' , ' conv4 ' , and ' conv5 ' to be 66.84 , 94.52 , and 94.52 respectively .
heading: Implementation Details

text: In the CMS - CNN , the RoI pooling layer already ensure that the pooled feature maps have the same size .
heading: Implementation Details

text: Specifically , features pooled from ' conv3 ' , ' conv4 ' , and ' conv5 ' are initialized with scale to be 57.75 , 81.67 , and 81.67 respectively , for both face and body pipelines .
heading: Implementation Details

text: The MS - RPN and the CMS - CNN share the same parameters for all convolution layers so that computation can be done once , resulting in higher efficiency .
heading: Implementation Details

text: Additionally , in order to shrink the channel size of the concatenated feature map , a 11 convolution layer is then employed .
heading: Implementation Details

text: We propose a method to address challenges in unconstrained face detection , such as arbitrary pose variations and occlusions .
heading: abstract

text: It is the first step in automatic face recognition applications .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: In this paper , we refer to face detection with arbitrary facial variations as the unconstrained face detection problem .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: First , we propose a simple pixel - level feature , called the Normalized Pixel Difference ( NPD ) .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: An NPD is computed as the ratio of the difference between any two pixel intensity values to the sum of their values , in the same form as the Weber Fraction in experimental psychology .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The NPD feature has several desirable properties , such as scale invariance , boundedness , and ability to reconstruct the original image .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: we further show that NPD features can be obtained from a lookup table , and the resulting face detection template can be easily scaled for multiscale face detection .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Secondly , we propose a deep quadratic tree learning method and construct a single soft - cascade AdaBoost classifier to handle complex face manifolds and arbitrary pose and occlusion conditions .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: In this way , different types of faces can be automatically divided into different leaves of a tree classifier , and the complex face manifold in a high dimensional space can be partitioned in the learning process .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: This is the " divide and conquer " strategy to tackle unconstrained face detection in a single classifier , without pre-labeling of views in the training set of face images .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The resulting face detector is robust to variations in pose , occlusion , and illumination , as well as to blur and low image resolution .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The source code of the proposed method is available in http://www.cbsr.ia.ac.cn/users/scliao/ projects / npdface / .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: We used a detection template of 24 24 pixels .
heading: Implementation Details

text: We set the maximum depth of the tree classifiers to be learned as eight , so that at most eight NPD features need to be evaluated for each tree classifier .
heading: Implementation Details

text: In the soft cascade training , we set the threshold of each exit as the minimal score of positive samples , i.e. we did not reject positive samples during training .
heading: Implementation Details

text: Our final detector contains 1,226 deep quadratic trees , and 46,401 NPD features .
heading: Implementation Details

text: For an analysis , we also trained a near frontal face detector using the proposed NPD features and the classic cascade of regression trees ( CART ) with depth of four .
heading: Implementation Details

text: A subset of the training data 2 in was used , including 12,102 face images and 12,315 nonface images .
heading: Implementation Details

text: The detection template is 20 20 pixels .
heading: Implementation Details

text: The detector cascade contains 15 stages , and for each stage , the target false accept rate was 0.5 , with a detection rate of 0.999 .
heading: Implementation Details

text: Robust Face Detection via Learning Small Faces on Hard Images
heading: title

text: Face detection is a fundamental and important computer vision problem , which is critical for many face - related tasks , such as face alignment , tracking and recognition .
heading: Introduction

text: To address this issue , we propose to mine hard examples at image level in parallel with anchor level .
heading: Introduction

text: More specifically , we propose to dynamically assign difficulty scores to training images during the learning process , which can determine whether an image is already well - detected or still useful for further training .
heading: Introduction

text: This allows us to fully utilize the images which were not perfectly detected to better facilitate the following learning process .
heading: Introduction

text: Apart from mining the hard images , we also propose to improve the detection quality by exclusively exploiting small faces .
heading: Introduction

text: Compared with these methods , our detector is more efficient since it is specially designed to aggressively leveraging the small faces during training .

text: Recurrent Scale Approximation for Object Detection in CNN

Since convolutional neural network ( CNN ) lacks an inherent mechanism to handle large scale variations , we always need to compute feature maps multiple times for multiscale object detection , which has the bottleneck of computational cost in practice .
heading: abstract

text: Our codes and annotations mentioned in Sec.4.1 can be accessed at github.com/sciencefans/RSA-for-object-detection dle the variations caused by appearance , location and scale .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work , we propose a recurrent scale approximation ( RSA , see ) unit to achieve the goal aforementioned .
heading: Introduction

text: The RSA unit is designed to be plugged at some specific depths in a network and to be fed with an initial feature map at the largest scale .
heading: Introduction

text: The unit convolves the input in a recurrent manner to generate the prediction of the feature map that is half the size of the input .
heading: Introduction

text: Such a scheme could feed the network with input at one scale only and approximate the rest features at smaller scales through a learnable RSA unit - a balance considering both efficiency and accuracy .
heading: Introduction

text: The first is a scale - forecast network to globally predict potential scales for a novel image and we compute feature pyramids for just a certain set of scales based on the prediction .
heading: Introduction

text: The second is a landmark retracing network that retraces the location of the regressed landmarks in the preceding layers and generates a confidence score for each landmark based on the landmark feature set .
heading: Introduction

text: The final score of identifying a face within an anchor is thereby revised by the LRN network .
heading: Introduction

text: The three components can be incorporated into a unified CNN framework and trained end - to - end .
heading: Introduction

text: Natural Language Comprehension with the EpiReader
heading: title

text: We present the EpiReader , a novel model for machine comprehension of text .
heading: abstract

text: Machine comprehension of unstructured , real - world text is a major research goal for natural language processing .
heading: abstract

text: Current tests of machine comprehension pose questions whose answers can be inferred from some supporting text , and evaluate a model 's response to the questions .
heading: abstract

text: We propose a deep , end - to - end , neural comprehension model that we call the EpiReader .
heading: Introduction

text: The EpiReader factors into two components .
The first component extracts a small set of potential answers based on a shallow comparison of the question with its supporting text ; we call this the Extractor .
heading: The EpiReader factors into two components .

text: The second component reranks the proposed answers based on deeper semantic comparisons with the text ; we call this the Reasoner .
heading: The EpiReader factors into two components .

text: The semantic comparisons implemented by the Reasoner are based on the concept of recognizing textual entailment ( RTE ) , also known as natural language inference .
heading: Test 2 .

text: Thus , the Extractor serves the important function of filtering a large set of potential answers down to a small , tractable set of likely candidates for more thorough testing .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: The Extractor follows the form of a pointer network , and uses a differentiable attention mechanism to indicate words in the text that potentially answer the question .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: This approach was used ( on it s own ) for question answering with the Attention Sum Reader .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: The Extractor outputs a small set of answer candidates along with their estimated probabilities of correctness .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: The Reasoner forms hypotheses by inserting the candidate answers into the question , then estimates the concordance of each hypothesis with each sentence in the supporting text .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: We use these estimates as a measure of the evidence for a hypothesis , and aggregate evidence overall sentences .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: In the end , we combine the Reasoner 's evidence with the Extractor 's probability estimates to produce a final ranking of the answer candidates .
heading: This process is computationally demanding .

text: To train our model we used stochastic gradient descent with the ADAM optimizer ( Kingma and Ba , 2014 ) , with an initial learning rate of 0.001 .

text: Neural Natural Language Inference Models Enhanced with External Knowledge
Modeling natural language inference is a very challenging task .
heading: abstract

text: With the availability of large annotated data , it has recently become feasible to train complex models such as neural - network - based inference models , which have shown to achieve the state - of - the - art performance .
heading: abstract

text: Although there exist relatively large annotated data , can machines learn all knowledge needed to perform natural language inference ( NLI ) from these data ?
heading: abstract

text: If not , how can neural - network - based NLI models benefit from external knowledge and how to build NLI models to leverage it ?
heading: abstract

text: Natural language inference ( NLI ) , also known as recognizing textual entailment ( RTE ) , is an important NLP problem concerned with determining inferential relationship ( e.g. , entailment , contradiction , or neutral ) between a premise p and a hypothesis h.
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper we enrich neural - network - based NLI models with external knowledge in coattention , local inference collection , and inference composition components .
heading: Introduction

text: We show the proposed model improves the state - of - the - art NLI models to achieve better performances on the SNLI and MultiNLI datasets .
heading: Introduction

text: The advantage of using external knowledge is more significant when the size of training data is restricted , suggesting that if more knowledge can be obtained , it may bring more benefit .

text: For natural language understanding ( NLU ) technology to be maximally useful , it must be able to process language in away that is not exclusive to a single task , genre , or dataset .

text: Parameter Re-Initialization through Cyclical Batch Size Schedules
Optimal parameter initialization remains a crucial problem for neural network training .
heading: abstract

text: Our work explores the idea of adapting the weight initialization to the optimization dynamics of the specific learning task at hand .
heading: Introduction

text: From the Bayesian perspective , improved weight initialization can be viewed as starting with a better prior , which leads to a more accurate posterior and thus better generalization ability .
heading: Introduction

text: For example , in the seminal works , an adaptive prior is implemented via Markov Chain Monte Carlo ( MCMC ) methods .
heading: Introduction

text: Motivated by these ideas , we incorporate an " adaptive initialization " for neural network training ( see section 2 for details ) , where we use cyclical batch size schedules to control the noise ( or temperature ) of SGD .
heading: Introduction

text: Here , we build upon this work by studying different cyclical annealing strategies for a wide range of problems .
heading: Introduction

text: Language Results
Language modeling is a challenging problem due to the complex and long - range interactions between distant words .
heading: Language Results

text: CBS schedules effectively help us avoid overfitting , and in addition snapshot ensembling enables even greater performance .
heading: Language Results

text: As we can see , the best performing CBS schedules result in significant improvements in perplexity ( up to 7.91 ) over the baseline schedules and also offer reductions in the number of SGD training iterations ( up to 33 % ) .
heading: Language Results

text: Notice that almost all CBS schedules outperform the baseline schedule .
heading: Language Results

text: In our experiments , CBS schedules do not yield large performance improvements on models like E1 which exhibit smaller disparities between training and testing performance .
heading: Language Results

As seen in , the training curves of CBS schedules also exhibit the aforementioned cyclical spikes both in training loss and testing accuracy .

text: Neural Tree Indexers for Text Understanding
In this study , we introduce Neural Tree Indexers ( NTI ) , a class of tree structured models for NLP tasks .

text: NTI takes a sequence of tokens and produces its representation by constructing a full n-ary tree in a bottom - up fashion .

text: Each node in NTI is associated with one of the node transformation functions : leaf node mapping and non-leaf node composition functions .

text: Furthermore , we propose different variants of node composition function and attention over tree for our NTI models .

text: When a sequential leaf node transformer such as LSTM is chosen , the NTI network forms a sequence - tree hybrid model taking advantage of both conditional and compositional powers of sequential and recursive models . :

text: Deep Fusion LSTMs for Text Semantic Matching

Among many natural language processing ( NLP ) tasks , such as text classification , question answering and machine translation , a common problem is modelling the relevance / similarity of a pair of texts , which is also called text semantic matching .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper , we adopt a deep fusion strategy to model the strong interactions of two sentences .
heading: Strong Interaction Models

text: Thus , text matching can be regarded as modelling the interaction of two texts in a recursive matching way .
heading: Strong Interaction Models

text: Following this idea , we propose deep fusion long short - term memory neural networks ( DF - LSTMs ) to model the interactions recursively .
heading: Strong Interaction Models

text: More concretely , DF - LSTMs consist of two interconnected conditional LSTMs , each of which models apiece of text under the influence of another .
heading: Strong Interaction Models

text: The output vector of DF - LSTMs is fed into a task - specific output layer to compute the match - ing score .
heading: Strong Interaction Models

heading: Competitor Methods

text: Parallel LSTMs : Two sequences are first encoded by two LSTMs separately , then they are concatenated and fed to a MLP .
heading: Competitor Methods

text: Attention LSTMs : Two sequences are encoded by LSTMs with attention mechanism , proposed by .
heading: Competitor Methods

text: Word - by - word Attention LSTMs : An improved strategy of attention LSTMs , which introduces word - by - word attention mechanism and is proposed by . :

text: Reading Wikipedia to Answer Open-Domain Questions
heading: title

text: This paper considers the problem of answering factoid questions in an open - domain setting using Wikipedia as the unique knowledge source , such as one does when looking for answers in an encyclopedia .
heading: Introduction

text: Unlike knowledge bases ( KBs ) such as Freebase or DB - Pedia , which are easier for computers to process but too sparsely populated for open - domain question answering , Wikipedia contains up - to - date knowledge that humans are interested in .
heading: Introduction

text: In order to answer any question , one must first retrieve the few relevant articles among more than 5 million items , and then scan them carefully to identify the answer .
heading: Introduction

text: We term this setting , machine reading at scale ( MRS ) .
heading: Introduction

text: Our work treats Wikipedia as a collection of articles and does not rely on its internal graph structure .
heading: Introduction

text: As a result , our approach is generic and could be switched to other collections of documents , books , or even daily updated newspapers .
heading: Introduction

text: Having a single knowledge source forces the model to be very precise while searching for an answer as the evidence might appear only once .

text: A Deep Cascade Model for Multi - Document Reading Comprehension
heading: title

text: Machine reading comprehension ( MRC ) , which empowers computers with the ability to read and comprehend knowledge and then answer questions from textual data , has made rapid progress in recent years .
heading: Introduction

text: From the early cloze - style test to answer extraction from a single paragraph , and to the more complex open - domain question answering from web data , great efforts have been made to push the MRC technique to more practical applications .
heading: Introduction

text: To address the above problems , we propose a deep cascade model which combines the advantages of both methods in a coarse - to - fine manner .
heading: Introduction

text: The deep cascade model is designed to properly keep the balance between the effectiveness and efficiency .
heading: Introduction

text: At early stages of the model , simple features and ranking functions are used to select a candidate set of most relevant contents , filtering out the irrelevant documents and paragraphs as much as possible .
heading: Introduction

text: Then the selected paragraphs are passed to the attention - based deep MRC model for extracting the actual answer span at word level .
heading: Introduction

text: To better support the answer extraction , we also introduce the document extraction and paragraph extraction as two auxiliary tasks , which helps to quickly narrow down the entire search space .
heading: Introduction

text: We jointly optimize all the three tasks in a unified deep MRC model , which shares some common bottom layers .
heading: Introduction

text: This cascaded structure enables the models to perform a coarse - to - fine pruning at different stages , better models can be learnt effectively and efficiently .
heading: Introduction

text: The overall framework of our model is demonstrated in , which consists of three modules : document retrieval , paragraph retrieval and answer extraction .
heading: Introduction

text: The first module takes the question and a collection of raw documents as input .
heading: Introduction

text: The module at each subsequent stage consumes the output from the previous stage , and further prunes the documents , paragraphs and answer spans given the question .
heading: Introduction

text: The ranking function is first used as a preliminary filter to discard most of the irrelevant documents or paragraphs , so as to keep our framework efficient .
heading: Introduction

text: The extraction function is then designed to deal with the auxiliary document and paragraph extraction tasks , which is jointly optimized with the final answer extraction module for better extraction performance .
heading: Introduction

text: We choose K = 4 and N = 2 for the good performance when evaluating on the dev set .
heading: Implementation Details

text: For the multi-task deep attention framework , we adopt the Adam optimizer for training , with a mini-batch size of 32 and initial learning rate of 0.0005 .

heading: Implementation Details

text: The word embeddings are fixed during training .
heading: Implementation Details

heading: Implementation Details

text: The task - specific hyper - parameters ? 1 and ? 2 in Equ. 15 are set as ? 1 = ? 2 = 0.5 . Regularization parameter ? in Equ.
heading: Implementation Details

text: All models are trained on Nvidia Tesla M40 GPU with Cudnn LSTM cell in Tensorflow 1.3 .

text: We can see that by adopting the deep cascade learning framework , the proposed model outperforms the previous state - of - the - art methods by an evident margin on both datasets , which validates the effectiveness of the proposed method in addressing the challenging multi-document MRC task .
heading: Main Results

text: From the results , we can see that : 1 ) the shared LSTM plays an important role in answer extraction among multiple documents , the benefit lies in two parts : a ) it helps to normalize the content probability score from multiple documents so that the answers extracted from different documents can be directly compared ; b ) it can keep the ranking order from document ranking component in mind , which may serve as an additional signal when predicting the best answer .

text: SDNET : CONTEXTUALIZED ATTENTION - BASED DEEP NETWORK FOR CONVERSATIONAL QUESTION AN - SWERING
heading: title

text: Conversational question answering ( CQA ) is a novel QA task that requires understanding of dialogue context .
heading: abstract

text: Different from traditional single - turn machine reading comprehension ( MRC ) tasks , CQA includes passage comprehension , coreference resolution , and contextual understanding .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we propose SDNet , a contextual attention - based deep neural network for the task of conversational question answering .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Firstly , we apply both inter-attention and self - attention on passage and question to obtain a more effective understanding of the passage and dialogue history .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Secondly , SDNet leverages the latest breakthrough in NLP : BERT contextual embedding .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Different from the canonical way of appending a thin layer after BERT structure according to , we innovatively employed a weighted sum of BERT layer outputs , with locked BERT parameters .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Thirdly , we prepend previous rounds of questions and answers to the current question to incorporate contextual information .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: As shown , SDNet achieves significantly better results than baseline models .
heading: Results .

text: In detail , the single SDNet model improves overall F 1 by 1.6 % , compared with previous state - of - art model on CoQA , Flow QA .
heading: Results .

text: Ensemble SDNet model further improves overall F 1 score by 2.7 % , and it 's the first model to achieve over 80 % F 1 score on in - domain datasets ( 80.7 % ) .
heading: Results .

text: As seen , SDNet overpasses all but one baseline models after the second epoch , and achieves state - of - the - art results only after 8 epochs .
heading: Results .

text: TRACKING THE WORLD STATE WITH RECURRENT ENTITY NETWORKS
heading: title

text: In this paper , we investigate this problem through a simple story understanding scenario , in which the agent is given a sequence of textual statements and events , and then given another series of statements about the final state of the world .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: We propose to handle this scenario with a new kind of memory - augmented neural network that uses a distributed memory and processor architecture : the Recurrent Entity Network ( EntNet ) .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The model consists of a fixed number of dynamic memory cells , each containing a vector key w j and a vector value ( or content ) h j .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Each cell is associated with its own " processor " , a simple gated recurrent network that may update the cell value given an input .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Alternatively , the EntNet can be seen as a bank of gated RNNs ( all sharing the same parameters ) , whose hidden states correspond to latent concepts and attributes , and whose parameters describe the laws of the world according to which the attributes of objects are updated .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Their hidden state is updated only when new information relevant to their concept is received , and remains otherwise unchanged .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: The keys used in the addressing / gating mechanism also correspond to concepts or entities , but are modified only during learning , not during inference .
heading: INTRODUCTION

text: Sentence Similarity Learning by Lexical Decomposition and Composition

Most conventional sentence similarity methods only focus on similar parts of two input sentences , and simply ignore the dissimilar parts , which usually give us some clues and semantic meanings about the sentences .
heading: abstract

text: In this paper , we propose a novel model to tackle all these challenges jointly by decomposing and composing lexical semantics over sentences .
heading: E5

text: Given a sentence pair , the model represents each word as a low -dimensional vector ( challenge 1 ) , and calculates a semantic matching vector for each word based on all words in the other sentence ( challenge 2 ) .
heading: E5

text: Then based on the semantic matching vector , each word vector is decomposed into two components : a similar component and a dissimilar component ( challenge 3 ) .
heading: E5

text: We use similar components of all the words to represent the similar parts of the sentence pair , and dissimilar components of every word to model the dissimilar parts explicitly .
heading: E5

text: After this , a two - channel CNN operation is performed to compose the similar and dissimilar components into a feature vector ( challenge 2 and 3 ) .
heading: E5

text: Finally , the composed feature vector is utilized to predict the sentence similarity .
heading: E5

text: Machine reading systems can be tested on their ability to answer questions posed on the contents of documents that they have seen , but until now large scale training and test datasets have been missing for this type of evaluation .
heading: abstract

text: Traditional approaches to machine reading and comprehension have been based on either hand engineered grammars , or information extraction methods of detecting predicate argument triples that can later be queried as a relational database .
heading: Introduction

text: In this work we seek to directly address the lack of real natural language training data by introducing a novel approach to building a supervised reading comprehension data set .
heading: Introduction

text: We observe that summary and paraphrase sentences , with their associated documents , can be readily converted to context - query - answer triples using simple entity detection and anonymisation algorithms .
heading: Introduction

text: Using this approach we have collected two new corpora of roughly a million news stories with associated queries from the CNN and Daily Mail websites .
heading: Introduction

text: We demonstrate the efficacy of our new corpora by building novel deep learning models for reading comprehension .
heading: Introduction

text: We expect that the attention - based models would therefore outperform the pure LSTM - based approaches .

heading: title

text: In this paper , we proposed a sentence encoding - based model for recognizing text entailment .
heading: abstract

text: Given a pair of sentences , the goal of recognizing text entailment ( RTE ) is to determine whether the hypothesis can reasonably be inferred from the premises .
heading: Introduction

text: There were three types of relation in RTE , Entailment ( inferred to be true ) , Contradiction ( inferred to be false ) and Neutral ( truth unknown ) .
heading: Introduction

text: In this paper , we proposed a unified deep learning framework for recognizing textual entailment which dose not require any feature engineering , or external resources .
heading: Introduction

text: The basic model is based on building biL - STM models on both premises and hypothesis .
heading: Introduction

text: The basic mean pooling encoder can roughly form a intuition about what this sentence is talking about .
heading: Introduction

text: In addition , we introduced a simple effective input strategy that get ride of same words in hypothesis and premise , which further boosts our performance .
heading: Introduction

text: The training objective of our model is cross - entropy loss , and we use minibatch SGD with the Rmsprop ( Tieleman and Hinton , 2012 ) for optimization .
heading: Parameter Setting

text: The batch size is 128 .
heading: Parameter Setting

text: A dropout layer was applied in the output of the network with the dropout rate set to 0.25 .
heading: Parameter Setting

text: In our model , we used pretrained 300D Glove 840B vectors to initialize the word embedding .
heading: Parameter Setting

text: Out - of - vocabulary words in the training set are randomly initialized by sampling values uniformly from ( 0.05 , 0.05 ) .
heading: Parameter Setting

text: We observed that more attention was given to Nones , Verbs and Adjectives .
heading: Results and Qualitative Analysis

text: While mean pooling regarded each word of equal importance , the attention mechanism helps re-weight words according to their importance .
heading: Results and Qualitative Analysis

text: A BERT Baseline for the Natural Questions
In this technical note we describe a BERT - based model for the Natural Questions .
heading: Introduction

text: The key insights in our approach are 1 . to jointly predict short and long answers in a single model rather than using a pipeline approach , 2 . to split each document into multiple training instances by using overlapping windows of tokens , like in the original BERT model for the SQuAD task , 3 . to aggressively downsample null instances ( i.e. instances without an answer ) at training time to create a balanced training set , 4 . to use the " [ CLS ] " token at training time to predict null instances and rank spans at inference time by the difference between the span score and the " [ CLS ] " score .
heading: Introduction

text: We initialized our model from a BERT model already finetuned on SQ u AD 1.1 .
heading: Experiments

text: We trained the model by minimizing loss L from Section 3 with the Adam optimizer ( Kingma and Ba , 2014 ) with a batch size of 8 .
heading: Experiments

text: As is common practice for BERT models , we only tuned the number of epochs and the initial learning rate for finetuning and found that training for 1 epoch with an initial learning rate of 3 10 ? 5 was the best setting .
heading: Experiments

text: Evaluation completed in about 5 hours on the NQ dev and test set with a single Tesla P100 GPU .
heading: Experiments

text: Our BERT model for NQ performs dramatically better than the models presented in the original NQ paper .
heading: Experiments

text: Our model closes the gap between the F 1 score achieved by the original baseline systems and the super - annotator upper bound by 30 % for the long answer NQ task and by 50 % for the short answer NQ task .
heading: Experiments
